# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The first example of a stable heteroalkene E=C or E=E' (E, E' = P) containing a heavy group 15 element was reported in 1982 by Yoshifuji.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] After the realization of heavier heteroalkenes, the field of organometallic chemistry began exploring the idea of heteroallenes E=C=E' and E=C=C=E', in which one or more carbon atom of an allene is substituted by a heavier atom.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The first of these heteroallenes containing a heavier group 15 element to be reported was synthesized in 1984 by Yoshifuji.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] 1-phosphaallene, also referred to as ethenylidenephosphine or λ3-phosphaallene, was first synthesized using the 2,4,6-tri-t-butylphenyl (supermesityl, or Mes*) moiety as a sterically protecting group.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The most widely known example of 1-phosphaalenes is the Mes* substituted 3H-phosphallene, where a hydrogen is bonded to the terminal carbon atom, which was synthesized by Märkl and Reitinger in 1988.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Some more recent advances made in regards to 1-phosphaallenes include the development of simpler synthetic routes and the discovery of synthetic pathways using phosphaallenes to create molecules that are typically only synthesized through complicated methods.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple synthetic routes to 1-phosphaallenes have been reported.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The most common are Phospha-Wittig-Horner reactions, rearrangement of alkylynlphosphines with a base present, dehydrochlorination of a chlorovinylphospine, and the reaction of lithium with a C,C-dichlorophosphirane.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] More recent synthetic advances include the dehydrobromination of phosphaalkenes the hydroalumination of alkynylphosphines.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The Phospha-Wittig-Horner reaction, first reported by Mathey et al. in 1992, was initially developed as a synthetic route to convert aldehydes and ketones into C-mono and C,C-disubstituted phosphaalkenes, respectively.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] This method was then adapted to rapidly synthesize phosphaallenes by reacting phosphaketenes with an organolithium base, such as lithium diisopropylamide or t-BuOLi.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] n-BuLi is used as a strong base in the synthesis of a phosphaallene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] A lithium complex can be used to synthesize phosphaallenes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Like the transition from an alkyne to an allene in organic chemistry, phosphaallenes can be synthesized from alkynylphosphines by adding a strong base such as n-butyllithium (n-BuLi).
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] These complexes are typically useful due to the broad range of stable products that can be obtained from this synthetic route.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple stable phosphaallenes have been synthesized from LiC≡CR and ArP(H)Cl (R = Ph, t-Bu, Me, CH2OSiMe3).
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The basicity of the lithium complex is essential to the success of these reactions.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The dehydrochlorination of 1-chlorovinylphosphine by DBU (1,8-diazabicyclo-[5.4.0]undec-7-ene) yields a variety of results, depending on the structure of the initial chlorovinylphosphine.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Many of these reactions require temperatures between −90 °C and 0 °C to ensure a stable product is formed.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] As many of these reactions are warmed, oligomerization of the phosphaallene occurs.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Other reactions following this synthetic route occur with gas phase reagents at 250 °C.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In this synthetic route, a dichlorocarbene is first reacted with a phosphaethylene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The addition of t-BuLi to the resulting 2,2-dichlorophosphirane yields the phosphaallene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] This route includes an insertion of carbon into the P=C bond of a phosphaalkene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene with the sterically cumbersome Mes* moiety was reacted with t-BuOK to yield the cyclopropylidenephosphaethene product.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Treatment of the (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene reagent with a weaker base, EtONa yields a non-cyclic isomer that can undergo cyclization in the presence of t-BuOK.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In 2019, a new synthetic route for the synthesis of phosphaallenes was reported by Klöcker and coworkers.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroalumination of dialkynylphosphines with different alkylaluminium hydrides resulted in the elimination of dialkylaluminium alkynides and the desired phosphaallenes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Many of the phosphaallenes Klöcker and coworkers synthesized spontaneously decomposed into less-desired products, but the newly reported synthetic method did allow for the isolation of some highly reactive compounds that had not been isolated previously.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In 2022, the most notable aspect of 1-phosphaallenes is their reactivity.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes contain three reactive centers: the P=C bond, the C=C bond, and the phosphorus atom.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The P=C bond and the C=C bond are thought to be electronically independent of one another.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] This gives rise to a wide variety of reactivity, which is similar to that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Without a large steric hindrance, most phosphaallenes quickly dimerize in a [2+2]- or [2+3]-cycloaddition to yield four- or five-membered rings.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Thus, in order to prevent dimerization, a bulky moiety such as Mes* is often used.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Dimerization frequently occurs in a head-to-tail manner, exhibiting coupling between either the two C=C bonds or the two P=C bonds.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The regioselectivity of these dimerization reactions depends on the substituents on the C in the 3 position.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Nucleophilic alkoxide as well as n-BuLi will add to the P=C bond of a phosphaallene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] As seen in the reaction scheme, the central C atom is the preferred location for proton attack due to the partial negative charge it possesses.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The reaction of phosphaallenes with dichlorocarbenes results in a [2+1]-cycloaddition to the P=C double bond, which results in stable heterocyclic compounds.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes have also been investigated as reagents to form carbenes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Reacting the phosphaallene H2P=C=PH with acetylene yields a carbene via [3 + 2]-cycloaddition.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Crystal structure showing phosphaallene-transition metal coordination.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes can coordinate in an ɳ1 or ɳ2 fashion depending on the metal and experimental conditions.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Recent studies into the coordination behavior of the 3H-phosphaallene with tungsten (W) show that both stable and unstable phosphaallenes can bond to W through and ɳ1-coordination mode via a P-W bond.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Due to the stabilizing effect of coordination, reacting transient phosphaallenes with W has become a common method to create stable phosphaallenes that can then be characterized.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] These studies have also demonstrated that 3H-phosphaallenes exhibit ɳ2-coordination to Pt via side-on overlap between Pt and the P=C double bond resulting in a three-membered PtPC heterocycle.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Head-to-tail dimerization of 3H-phosphaallene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Tricyclic phosphine resulting from decomposition via irradiation.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Decomposition of the 3H-phosphaallene occurs at room-temperature to produce several products via P=C (head-to-tail) or C=C dimerization.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] One decomposition pathway results in an unusual tricyclic phosphine which can be selectively formed by irradiating a solution of the phosphaallene, iBu2AlH, and TripP(C≡CtBu)2 in n-hexanes for 60h with a mercury vapor lamp.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Under these conditions, the tricyclic phosphine was isolated in high yield and a purity of >95%.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Recently, two novel 1-benzodihydrophosphetes were synthesized by heating 3H-phosphaallene Mes*P=C=C(H)R (R = tBu, Ad) in toluene at 110 °C for 16-20h.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The resulting 1- benzodihydrophosphetes were not stable unless coordinated to tungsten.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The phosphorus-bound H of the product can be used in catalyst-free hydrophosphination reactions and in the synthesis of bulky phosphine ligands.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration is used as a method to reduce unsaturated compounds, and has been used to reduce P-C double or triple bonds in phosphaalkenes and phosphaalkynes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration of the 3H-phosphaallene Mes*-P=C=C(H)-tBu with 1:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded a di(phosphaalkenyl)borane, and the reaction in 2:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded the desired product with a B atom bound to two P=C double bonds.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroboration of the C=C bond was preferred over the hydroboration of the P=C bond.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes are typically colorless or pale yellow in color, and are often crystalline in structure; however, few crystal structures have been reported for this class of compounds.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] One compound, ArP=C=CPh2 (Ar =Mes*) was synthesized and characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] This compound showed a relatively short P=C double bond length of 1.625(4)Å and a short C=C bond length of 1.1327(5)Å, which closely resembles the bond length in an allene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure also showed a bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle at 168.0(3)°.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] This bent geometry is thought to be a result of both steric and electronic effects.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] One possible explanation for the observed bent geometry is the bonding model postulated by Lappert et al. which described the bonding between P and the C as singlet states that act in a double π-donor-acceptor fashion.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure of another 1-phosphaallene RP=C=CHR' (R= Mes*, R' = tBu) displays the same bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle being reported as 170.7°.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] Further, this compound also contains a short P=C bond length (1.634Å) and a short C=C bond length (1.136Å).
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The electronic structure of 1-phosphaallene is nearly identical to that of phosphaalkene.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The HOMO in both molecules is the π-orbital of the C=P bond, which is primarily P in character.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The LUMO in both structures, is also heavily localized over the C=P bond.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] However, the dipole moment in phosphaallenes is larger than that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In compounds with the antisymmetric form X=C=Y, IR stretching bands are observed in the 1600–2300 cm−1 region.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] However, the IR spectra of 1-phosphaallenes do not contain bands in this region, which suggests that the phosphaallene P=C=C is relatively symmetric.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In the phosphaallene H2C=C=PH, stretching frequencies are observed at 1788 and 789 cm−1, which are attributed to the C=C bond and the C=P bond, respectively.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] In similar compounds containing a C=C=N skeleton, there is a very strong band present within the 1600 – 2300 cm−1 region.
[src:amine/1-phosphaallenes] The presence of two stretching frequencies rather than one strong frequency in the phosphaallene supports that the C=C and C=P bonds are nearly independent of one another electronically.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] A key use is as a catalyst for epoxy resin chemistry.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It can be used as a homopolymerization catalyst for epoxy resins and also as an accelerator with epoxy resin curing agents.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It is then further used in coatings, sealants, composites, adhesives and elastomers.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It has been stated that it is probably the most widely used room temperature accelerator for two-component epoxy resin systems.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] The kinetics of curing with and without this accelerator have been extensively studied.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It is the usual benchmark or control used when other catalysts and accelerators are being developed and tested.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] In addition to its use in epoxy chemistry, it is also used in polyurethane chemistry for example by grafting the molecule into the polymer backbone.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It is also used as a trimerization catalyst with polymeric MDI.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] Polyether ether ketones may also be grafted with the molecule which then finds use in lithium batteries.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] The high functionality of the molecule means it can be used to complex some transition metals and this has also been studied.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] Often cited weaknesses are yellowing and odor.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] The material is a Mannich base and is manufactured by reacting phenol, formaldehyde and dimethylamine in a reactor under vacuum and removing the water produced.
[src:amine/2-4-6-tris-dimethylaminomethyl-phenol] It is classed as a high volume chemical and as such, its toxicity profile has been extensively studied.
[src:amine/3-nitroaniline] 3-Nitroaniline is produced on a commercial scale by reduction of 1,3-dinitrobenzene with hydrogen sulfide, or sodium sulfide (a Zinin reaction).
[src:amine/3-nitroaniline] It is used as a chemical intermediate for azo coupling component and the dyes disperse yellow 5 and acid blue 29.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] Below is a laboratory synthesis of 4-nitroaniline from aniline.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] The key step in this reaction sequence is an electrophilic aromatic substitution to install the nitro group *para* to the amino group.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] The amino group can be easily protonated and become a meta director.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] Therefore, a protection of the acetyl group is required.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] After this reaction, a separation must be performed to remove 2-nitroaniline, which is also formed in a small amount during the reaction.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] 4-Nitroaniline is mainly consumed industrially as a precursor to *p*-phenylenediamine, an important dye component.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] The reduction is effected using iron metal and by catalytic hydrogenation.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] It is also a precursor to 2,6-dichloro-4-nitroaniline, also used in dyes.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] Nitroaniline undergoes diazotization, which allows access to 1,4-dinitrobenzene and nitrophenylarsonic acid.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] With phosgene, it converts to 4-nitrophenylisocyanate.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] When mixed with sulfuric acid and heated, it dehydrates and polymerizes explosively into a rigid foam.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] The exact composition of the foam is unclear, but the process is believed to involve acidic protonation as well as displacement of the amine group by a sulfonic acid moiety.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] In Carbon snake demo, paranitroaniline can be used instead of sugar, if the experiment is allowed to proceed under an obligatory fumehood.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] With this method the reaction phase prior to the black snake's appearance is longer, but once complete, the black snake itself rises from the container very rapidly.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] This reaction may cause an explosion if too much sulfuric acid is used.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] The compound is toxic by way of inhalation, ingestion, and absorption, and should be handled with care.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] Its LD50 in rats is 750.0 mg/kg when administered orally.
[src:amine/4-nitroaniline] 4-Nitroaniline is particularly harmful to all aquatic organisms, and can cause long-term damage to the environment if released as a pollutant.
[src:amine/acetal] In organic chemistry, an **acetal** is a functional group with the connectivity R2C(OR')2.
[src:amine/acetal] Here, the R groups can be organic fragments (a carbon atom, with arbitrary other atoms attached to that) or hydrogen, while the R' groups must be organic fragments, not hydrogen.
[src:amine/acetal] The two R' groups can be equivalent to each other (a "symmetric acetal") or not (a "mixed acetal").
[src:amine/acetal] An acetal is formed from and convertible to two alcohol molecules and an aldehyde or ketone, but acetals have substantially different chemical stability and reactivity as compared to the analogous carbonyl compounds.
[src:amine/acetal] The central carbon atom has four bonds to it, and is therefore saturated and has tetrahedral geometry.
[src:amine/acetal] The IUPAC originally deprecated the usage of the word ketal altogether, but has since reversed its decision.
[src:amine/acetal] However, in contrast to historical usage, ketals are now a subset of acetals, a term that now encompasses both aldehyde- and ketone-derived structures.
[src:amine/acetal] If one of the R groups has an oxygen as the first atom (that is, there are more than two oxygens single-bonded to the central carbon), the functional group is instead an orthoester.
[src:amine/acetal] In contrast to variations of R, both R' groups are organic fragments.
[src:amine/acetal] If one R' is a hydrogen, the functional group is instead a hemiacetal, while if both are H, the functional group is a ketone hydrate or aldehyde hydrate.
[src:amine/acetal] Formation of an acetal occurs when the hydroxyl group of a hemiacetal becomes protonated and is lost as water.
[src:amine/acetal] The carbocation that is produced is then rapidly attacked by a molecule of alcohol.
[src:amine/acetal] Loss of the proton from the attached alcohol gives the acetal.
[src:amine/acetal] Acetals are stable compared to hemiacetals but their formation is a reversible equilibrium as with esters.
[src:amine/acetal] As a reaction to create an acetal proceeds, water must be removed from the reaction mixture, for example, with a Dean–Stark apparatus, lest it hydrolyse the product back to the hemiacetal.
[src:amine/acetal] The formation of acetals reduces the total number of molecules present (carbonyl + 2 alcohol → acetal + water) and therefore is generally not favourable with regard to entropy.
[src:amine/acetal] One situation where the reaction is not entropically unfavourable is when a single diol molecule is used rather than two separate alcohol molecules (carbonyl + diol → acetal + water).
[src:amine/acetal] Acetalization and ketalization are the organic reactions that involve the formation of an acetal (or ketals) from aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:amine/acetal] Since each step is often a rapid equilibrium, the reaction must be driven by removal of water.
[src:amine/acetal] Methods for removing water include azeotropic distillation and trapping water with desiccants like aluminium oxide and molecular sieves.
[src:amine/acetal] Steps assumed to be involved: protonation of the carbonyl oxygen, addition of the alcohol to the protonated carbonyl, protonolysis of the resulting hemiacetal or hemiketal, and addition of the second alcohol.
[src:amine/acetal] Another way to avoid the entropic cost is to perform the synthesis by acetal exchange (**transacetalization**), using a pre-existing acetal-type reagent as the OR'-group donor rather than simple addition of alcohols themselves.
[src:amine/acetal] One type of reagent used for this method is an orthoester.
[src:amine/acetal] In this case, water produced along with the acetal product is destroyed when it hydrolyses residual orthoester molecules, and this side reaction also produces more alcohol to be used in the main reaction.
[src:amine/acetal] Since many sugars are polyhydroxy aldehydes and ketones, sugars are a rich source of acetals and ketals.
[src:amine/acetal] Most glycosidic bonds in carbohydrates and other polysaccharides are acetal linkages.
[src:amine/acetal] Cellulose is a ubiquitous example of a polyacetal.
[src:amine/acetal] Benzylidene acetal and acetonide as protecting groups used in research of modified sugars.
[src:amine/acetal] Acetals also find application as chiral auxiliaries.
[src:amine/acetal] Indeed acetals of chiral glycols like, e.g. derivatives of tartaric acid can be asymmetrically opened with high selectivity.
[src:amine/acetal] This enables the construction of new chiral centers.
[src:amine/acetal] Formaldehyde forms a rich collection of acetals.
[src:amine/acetal] This tendency reflects the fact that low molecular weight aldehydes are prone to self-condensation such that the C=O bond is replaced by an acetal.
[src:amine/acetal] The acetal formed from formaldehyde (two hydrogens attached to the central carbon) is sometimes called a *formal* or the methylenedioxy group.
[src:amine/acetal] The acetal formed from acetone is sometimes called an acetonide.
[src:amine/acetal] Formaldehyde forms paraformaldehyde and 1,3,5-trioxane.
[src:amine/acetal] Polyoxymethylene (POM) plastic, also known as "acetal" or "polyacetal", is a polyacetal (and a polyether), and a polymer of formaldehyde.
[src:amine/acetal] Acetaldehyde converts to paraldehyde and metaldehyde.
[src:amine/acetal] Phenylsulfonylethylidene (PSE) acetal is an example of arylsulfonyl acetal possessing atypical properties, like resistance to acid hydrolysis which leads to selective introduction and removal of the protective group.
[src:amine/acetal] 1,1-Diethoxyethane (acetaldehyde diethyl acetal), sometimes called simply "acetal", is an important flavouring compound in distilled beverages.
[src:amine/acetal] Two ketals of ethyl acetoacetate are used in commercial fragrances.
[src:amine/acetal] Fructone (CH3C(O2C2H4)CH2CO2C2H5), an ethylene glycol ketal, and fraistone (CH3C(O2C2H3CH3)CH2CO2C2H5), a propylene glycol ketal, are commercial fragrances.
[src:amine/acetal] Used in a more general sense, the term **X**,**Y**-*acetal* also refers to any functional group that consists of a carbon bearing two heteroatoms **X** and **Y**.
[src:amine/acetal] For example, *N*,*O*-acetal refers to compounds of type R1R2C(OR)(NR'2) (R,R' ≠ H) also known as a *hemiaminal ether* or aminal, a.k.a. aminoacetal.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile was first prepared in 1847 by the French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is used mainly as a solvent in the purification of butadiene in refineries.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Specifically, acetonitrile is fed into the top of a distillation column filled with hydrocarbons including butadiene, and as the acetonitrile falls down through the column, it absorbs the butadiene which is then sent from the bottom of the tower to a second separating tower.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Heat is then employed in the separating tower to separate the butadiene.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] In the laboratory, it is used as a medium-polarity non-protic solvent that is miscible with water and a range of organic solvents, but not saturated hydrocarbons.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It has a convenient range of temperatures at which it is a liquid, and dissolves a wide range of ionic and nonpolar compounds and is useful as a mobile phase in HPLC and LC–MS.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It is widely used in battery applications because of its relatively high dielectric constant and ability to dissolve electrolytes.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] For similar reasons, it is a popular solvent in cyclic voltammetry.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Its ultraviolet transparency UV cutoff, low viscosity and low chemical reactivity make it a popular choice for high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC).
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile plays a significant role as the dominant solvent used in oligonucleotide synthesis from nucleoside phosphoramidites.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Industrially, it is used as a solvent for the manufacture of pharmaceuticals and photographic film.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is a common two-carbon building block in organic synthesis of many useful chemicals, including acetamidine hydrochloride, thiamine, and 1-naphthaleneacetic acid, along with more complex nitriles.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Its reaction with cyanogen chloride affords malononitrile.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile has a free electron pair at the nitrogen atom, which can form many transition metal nitrile complexes.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] A related complex is tetrakis(acetonitrile)copper(I) hexafluorophosphate [Cu(CH3CN)4]+.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The CH3CN ligands in these complexes are rapidly displaced.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It also forms Lewis adducts with group 13 Lewis acids like boron trifluoride.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] In superacids, it is possible to protonate acetonitrile.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is a byproduct from the manufacture of acrylonitrile by catalytic ammoxidation of propylene.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Most is combusted to support the intended process but an estimated several thousand tons are retained for the above-mentioned applications.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Production trends for acetonitrile thus generally follow those of acrylonitrile.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] In 1992, 14,700 tonnes (16,200 short tons) of acetonitrile were produced in the US.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile has only modest toxicity in small doses.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It can be metabolised to produce hydrogen cyanide, which is the source of the observed toxic effects.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Generally the onset of toxic effects is delayed, due to the time required for the body to metabolize acetonitrile to cyanide (generally about 2–12 hours).
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Cases of acetonitrile poisoning in humans are rare but not unknown by inhalation and ingestion.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The symptoms, which do not usually appear for several hours after the exposure, include breathing difficulties, slow pulse rate, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Convulsions and coma can occur in serious cases, followed by death from respiratory failure.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The treatment is as for cyanide poisoning, with oxygen, sodium nitrite, and sodium thiosulfate among the most commonly used emergency treatments.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It has been used in a formulation for removal of sculptured fingernails.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] At least two cases have been reported of accidental poisoning of young children by acetonitrile-based sculptured nail remover, one of which was fatal.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Acetone and ethyl acetate are often preferred as safer for domestic use, and acetonitrile has been banned in cosmetic products in the European Economic Area since March 2000.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] In common with other nitriles, acetonitrile can be metabolised in microsomes, especially in the liver, to produce hydrogen cyanide, as was first shown by Pozzani *et al.* in 1959.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The first step in this pathway is the oxidation of acetonitrile to glycolonitrile by an NADPH-dependent cytochrome P450 monooxygenase.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The glycolonitrile then undergoes a spontaneous decomposition to give hydrogen cyanide and formaldehyde.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Formaldehyde, a toxin and a carcinogen on its own, is further oxidized to formic acid, which is another source of toxicity.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The metabolism of acetonitrile is much slower than that of other nitriles, which accounts for its relatively low toxicity.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] Hence, one hour after administration of a potentially lethal dose, the concentration of cyanide in the rat brain was ⁠1/20⁠ that for a propionitrile dose 60 times lower (see table).
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The relatively slow metabolism of acetonitrile to hydrogen cyanide allows more of the cyanide produced to be detoxified within the body to thiocyanate (the rhodanese pathway).
[src:amine/acetonitrile] It also allows more acetonitrile to be excreted unchanged before it is metabolised.
[src:amine/acetonitrile] The main pathways of excretion are by exhalation and in the urine.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] In organic chemistry, the **acetoxy group** (abbr.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] **AcO–** or **–OAc**; IUPAC name: **acetyloxy**), is a functional group with the formula −OCOCH3 and the structure −O−C(=O)−CH3.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] As the *-oxy* suffix implies, it differs from the acetyl group (−C(=O)−CH3) by the presence of an additional oxygen atom.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] The name acetoxy is the short form of *acetyl-oxy*.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] An acetoxy group may be used as a protection for an alcohol functionality in a synthetic route although the protecting group itself is called an acetyl group.
[src:amine/acetoxy-group] An alcohol is not a particularly strong nucleophile and, when present, more powerful nucleophiles like amines will react with the above-mentioned reagents in preference to the alcohol.
[src:amine/amine] In chemistry, **amines** (/əˈmiːn, ˈæmiːn/, UK also /ˈeɪmiːn/) are organic compounds that contain carbon–nitrogen bonds.
[src:amine/amine] Amines are formed when one or more hydrogen atoms in ammonia are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups.
[src:amine/amine] The nitrogen atom in an amine possesses a lone pair of electrons.
[src:amine/amine] Amines can also exist as heterocyclic compounds.
[src:amine/amine] Aniline ( ${\ce {C6H7N}}$ ) is the simplest aromatic amine, consisting of a benzene ring bonded to an amino ( ${\ce {-NH2}}$ ) group.
[src:amine/amine] Amines are classified into three types: primary (1°), secondary (2°), and tertiary (3°) amines.
[src:amine/amine] **Primary amines** (1°) contain one alkyl or aryl substituent and have the general formula ${\ce {RNH2}}$ .
[src:amine/amine] **Secondary amines** (2°) have two alkyl or aryl groups attached to the nitrogen atom, with the general formula ${\ce {R2NH}}$ .
[src:amine/amine] **Tertiary amines** (3°) contain three substituent groups bonded to the nitrogen atom, and are represented by the formula ${\ce {R3N}}$ .
[src:amine/amine] The functional group −NH2 present in primary amines is called the amino group.
[src:amine/amine] Amines can be classified according to the nature and number of substituents on nitrogen.
[src:amine/amine] **Aliphatic amines** contain only H and alkyl substituents.
[src:amine/amine] **Aromatic amines** have the nitrogen atom connected to an aromatic ring.
[src:amine/amine] Compounds where the nitrogen atom is attached to a carbonyl group, thus having the structure R−C(=O)−NR′R″, are called amides.
[src:amine/amine] Compounds containing four organic substituents on the nitrogen, thus having the structure R4N+X−, are quaternary ammonium salts.
[src:amine/amine] Many kinds of anions are found in such compounds.
[src:amine/amine] Typically, the compound is given the prefix "amino-" or the suffix "-amine".
[src:amine/amine] The prefix "*N*-" shows substitution on the nitrogen atom.
[src:amine/amine] An organic compound with multiple amino groups is called a diamine, triamine, tetraamine and so forth.
[src:amine/amine] Lower amines are named with the suffix *-amine*.
[src:amine/amine] Higher amines have the prefix *amino* as a functional group.
[src:amine/amine] IUPAC however does not recommend this convention, but prefers the alkanamine form, e.g. butan-2-amine.
[src:amine/amine] Hydrogen bonding significantly influences the properties of primary and secondary amines.
[src:amine/amine] For example, methyl and ethyl amines are gases under standard conditions, whereas the corresponding methyl and ethyl alcohols are liquids.
[src:amine/amine] Amines possess a characteristic ammonia smell, liquid amines have a distinctive "fishy" and foul smell.
[src:amine/amine] The nitrogen atom features a lone electron pair that can bind H+ to form an ammonium ion R3NH+.
[src:amine/amine] The lone electron pair is represented in this article by two dots above or next to the N.
[src:amine/amine] The water solubility of simple amines is enhanced by hydrogen bonding involving these lone electron pairs.
[src:amine/amine] Typically salts of ammonium compounds exhibit the following order of solubility in water: primary ammonium (RNH+3) > secondary ammonium (R2NH+2) > tertiary ammonium (R3NH+).
[src:amine/amine] Small aliphatic amines display significant solubility in many solvents, whereas those with large substituents are lipophilic.
[src:amine/amine] Aromatic amines, such as aniline, have their lone pair electrons conjugated into the benzene ring, thus their tendency to engage in hydrogen bonding is diminished.
[src:amine/amine] Their boiling points are high and their solubility in water is low.
[src:amine/amine] Typically the presence of an amine functional group is deduced by a combination of techniques, including mass spectrometry as well as NMR and IR spectroscopies.
[src:amine/amine] 1H NMR signals for amines disappear upon treatment of the sample with D2O.
[src:amine/amine] In their infrared spectrum primary amines exhibit two N–H bands, whereas secondary amines exhibit only one.
[src:amine/amine] In their IR spectra, primary and secondary amines exhibit distinctive N–H stretching bands near 3300 cm−1.
[src:amine/amine] Somewhat less distinctive are the bands appearing below 1600 cm−1, which are weaker and overlap with C–C and C–H modes.
[src:amine/amine] For the case of propyl amine, the H–N–H scissor mode appears near 1600 cm−1, the C–N stretch near 1000 cm−1, and the R2N–H bend near 810 cm−1.
[src:amine/amine] Alkyl amines characteristically feature tetrahedral nitrogen centers.
[src:amine/amine] C-N distances are slightly shorter than C-C distances.
[src:amine/amine] The energy barrier for the nitrogen inversion of the stereocenter is about 7 kcal/mol for a trialkylamine.
[src:amine/amine] The interconversion has been compared to the inversion of an open umbrella into a strong wind.
[src:amine/amine] Amines of the type NHRR' and NRR′R″ are chiral: the nitrogen center bears four substituents counting the lone pair.
[src:amine/amine] Because of the low barrier to inversion, amines of the type NHRR' cannot be obtained in optical purity.
[src:amine/amine] For chiral tertiary amines, NRR′R″ can only be resolved when the R, R', and R″ groups are constrained in cyclic structures such as *N*-substituted aziridines (quaternary ammonium salts are resolvable).
[src:amine/amine] In aromatic amines ("anilines"), nitrogen is often nearly planar owing to conjugation of the lone pair with the aryl substituent.
[src:amine/amine] The C-N distance is correspondingly shorter.
[src:amine/amine] In aniline, the C–N distance is the same as the C–C distances.
[src:amine/amine] Compared to alkali metal hydroxides, amines are weaker.
[src:amine/amine] The degree of solvation of the protonated amine, which includes steric hindrance by the groups on nitrogen.
[src:amine/amine] Owing to inductive effects, the basicity of an amine might be expected to increase with the number of alkyl groups on the amine.
[src:amine/amine] Correlations are complicated owing to the effects of solvation which are opposite the trends for inductive effects.
[src:amine/amine] Solvation effects also dominate the basicity of aromatic amines (anilines).
[src:amine/amine] For anilines, the lone pair of electrons on nitrogen delocalizes into the ring, resulting in decreased basicity.
[src:amine/amine] Substituents on the aromatic ring, and their positions relative to the amino group, also affect basicity as seen in the table.
[src:amine/amine] Solvation significantly affects the basicity of amines.
[src:amine/amine] N−H groups strongly interact with water, especially in ammonium ions.
[src:amine/amine] Consequently, the basicity of ammonia is enhanced by 1011 by solvation.
[src:amine/amine] The intrinsic basicity of amines, i.e. the situation where solvation is unimportant, has been evaluated in the gas phase.
[src:amine/amine] In the gas phase, amines exhibit the basicities predicted from the electron-releasing effects of the organic substituents.
[src:amine/amine] Thus tertiary amines are more basic than secondary amines, which are more basic than primary amines, and finally ammonia is least basic.
[src:amine/amine] The order of pKb values (basicities in water) does not follow this order.
[src:amine/amine] Similarly, aniline is more basic than ammonia in the gas phase, but ten thousand times less so in aqueous solution.
[src:amine/amine] In aprotic polar solvents such as DMSO, DMF, and acetonitrile the energy of solvation is not as high as in protic polar solvents like water and methanol.
[src:amine/amine] For this reason, the basicity of amines in these aprotic solvents is almost solely governed by the electronic effects.
[src:amine/amine] In such reactions, which are more useful for alkyl iodides and bromides, the degree of alkylation is difficult to control such that one obtains mixtures of primary, secondary, and tertiary amines, as well as quaternary ammonium salts.
[src:amine/amine] Selectivity can be improved via the Delépine reaction, although this is rarely employed on an industrial scale.
[src:amine/amine] Selectivity is also assured in the Gabriel synthesis, which involves organohalide reacting with potassium phthalimide.
[src:amine/amine] Aryl halides are much less reactive toward amines and for that reason are more controllable.
[src:amine/amine] A popular way to prepare aryl amines is the Buchwald-Hartwig reaction.
[src:amine/amine] Disubstituted alkenes react with HCN in the presence of strong acids to give formamides, which can be decarbonylated.
[src:amine/amine] This method, the Ritter reaction, is used industrially to produce tertiary amines such as *tert*-octylamine.
[src:amine/amine] Hydroamination of alkenes is also widely practiced.
[src:amine/amine] The reaction is catalyzed by zeolite-based solid acids.
[src:amine/amine] A nickel catalyst can hydrogenate unsaturated N-containing functional groups to amines.
[src:amine/amine] Suitable groups include nitriles, imines (including oximes), amides, azides, and nitro groups.
[src:amine/amine] Many amines are produced from aldehydes and ketones via reductive amination, reduction of an imine formed *in situ* or a two-step process.
[src:amine/amine] LiAlH4 is more commonly employed to reduce these groups at laboratory scale.
[src:amine/amine] In the case of nitriles, reactions are sensitive to acidic or alkaline conditions, which can hydrolyze the −CN group.
[src:amine/amine] Aniline (C6H5NH2) and derivatives are prepared by reduction of the corresponding nitroaromatics.
[src:amine/amine] In industry, hydrogen is the preferred reductant, whereas tin and iron are often employed in the laboratory.
[src:amine/amine] Many methods exist for the preparation of amines, many of these methods being rather specialized.
[src:amine/amine] Aside from their basicity, the dominant reactivity of amines is their nucleophilicity.
[src:amine/amine] Most primary amines are good ligands for metal ions to give coordination complexes.
[src:amine/amine] Acyl chlorides and acid anhydrides react with primary and secondary amines to form amides (the "Schotten–Baumann reaction").
[src:amine/amine] Similarly, with sulfonyl chlorides, one obtains sulfonamides.
[src:amine/amine] This transformation, known as the Hinsberg reaction, is a chemical test for the presence of amines.
[src:amine/amine] Because amines are basic, they neutralize acids to form the corresponding ammonium salts R3NH+.
[src:amine/amine] When formed from carboxylic acids and primary and secondary amines, these salts thermally dehydrate to form the corresponding amides.
[src:amine/amine] Amines reacts with nitrous acid to give diazonium salts.
[src:amine/amine] The alkyl diazonium salts are of little importance because they are too unstable.
[src:amine/amine] Anilines and naphthylamines form more stable diazonium salts, which can be isolated in the crystalline form.
[src:amine/amine] Diazonium salts undergo a variety of useful transformations involving replacement of the N2 group with anions.
[src:amine/amine] Aryldiazoniums couple with electron-rich aromatic compounds such as a phenol to form azo compounds.
[src:amine/amine] Such reactions are widely applied to the production of dyes.
[src:amine/amine] Imine formation is an important reaction.
[src:amine/amine] Primary amines react with ketones and aldehydes to form imines.
[src:amine/amine] The breakdown of amino acids releases amines, famously in the case of decaying fish which smell of trimethylamine.
[src:amine/amine] Many neurotransmitters are amines, including epinephrine, norepinephrine, dopamine, serotonin, and histamine.
[src:amine/amine] Protonated amino groups (–NH+3) are the most common positively charged moieties in proteins, specifically in the amino acid lysine.
[src:amine/amine] The anionic polymer DNA is typically bound to various amine-rich proteins.
[src:amine/amine] Additionally, the terminal charged primary ammonium on lysine forms salt bridges with carboxylate groups of other amino acids in polypeptides, which is one of the primary influences on the three-dimensional structures of proteins.
[src:amine/amine] Hormones derived from the modification of amino acids are referred to as amine hormones.
[src:amine/amine] Typically, the original structure of the amino acid is modified such that a –COOH, or carboxyl, group is removed, whereas the –NH+3, or amine, group remains.
[src:amine/amine] Amine hormones are synthesized from the amino acids tryptophan or tyrosine.
[src:amine/amine] Primary aromatic amines are used as a starting material for the manufacture of azo dyes.
[src:amine/amine] It reacts with nitrous acid to form diazonium salt, which can undergo coupling reaction to form an azo compound.
[src:amine/amine] Aqueous monoethanolamine (MEA), diglycolamine (DGA), diethanolamine (DEA), diisopropanolamine (DIPA) and methyldiethanolamine (MDEA) are widely used industrially for removing carbon dioxide (CO2) and hydrogen sulfide (H2S) from natural gas and refinery process streams.
[src:amine/amine] They may also be used to remove CO2 from combustion gases and flue gases and may have potential for abatement of greenhouse gases.
[src:amine/amine] Related processes are known as sweetening.
[src:amine/amine] Amines are often used as epoxy resin curing agents.
[src:amine/amine] These include dimethylethylamine, cyclohexylamine, and a variety of diamines such as 4,4-diaminodicyclohexylmethane.
[src:amine/amine] Multifunctional amines such as tetraethylenepentamine and triethylenetetramine are also widely used in this capacity.
[src:amine/amine] The reaction proceeds by the lone pair of electrons on the amine nitrogen attacking the outermost carbon on the oxirane ring of the epoxy resin.
[src:amine/amine] This relieves ring strain on the epoxide and is the driving force of the reaction.
[src:amine/amine] Molecules with tertiary amine functionality are often used to accelerate the epoxy-amine curing reaction and include substances such as 2,4,6-Tris(dimethylaminomethyl)phenol.
[src:amine/amine] It has been stated that this is the most widely used room temperature accelerator for two-component epoxy resin systems.
[src:amine/amine] Low molecular weight simple amines, such as ethylamine, are toxic with LD50 between 100 and 1000 mg/kg.
[src:amine/amine] They are skin irritants, especially as some are easily absorbed through the skin.
[src:amine/amine] Amines are a broad class of compounds, and more complex members of the class can be extremely bioactive, for example strychnine.
